04712nam a22007095i 9780801469282DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979904765  a97808014692827 a10.7591/97808014692822doi  a(DE-B1597)478427  a(OCoLC)862958093  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB3199.A34bH633 2016 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a111.850922231 aHohendahl, Peter Uwe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Fleeting Promise of Art :bAdorno's Aesthetic Theory Revisited /cPeter Uwe Hohendahl. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I -- t1. Human Freedom and the Autonomy of Art: The Legacy of Kant -- t2. The Ephemeral and the Absolute: The Truth Content of Art -- t3. Aesthetic Violence: The Concepts of the Ugly and Primitive -- tPart II -- t4. Reality, Realism, and Representation -- t5. A Precarious Balance: Rereading German Classicism -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA discussion of Theodor Adorno’s Aesthetic Theory is bound to look significantly different today than it would have looked when the book was first published in 1970, or when it first appeared in English translation in the 1980s. In The Fleeting Promise of Art, Peter Uwe Hohendahl reexamines Aesthetic Theory along with Adorno’s other writings on aesthetics in light of the unexpected return of the aesthetic to today’s cultural debates.Is Adorno’s aesthetic theory still relevant today? Hohendahl answers this question with an emphatic yes. As he shows, a careful reading of the work exposes different questions and arguments today than it did in the past. Over the years Adorno’s concern over the fate of art in a late capitalist society has met with everything from suspicion to indifference. In part this could be explained by relative unfamiliarity with the German dialectical tradition in North America. Today’s debate is better informed, more multifaceted, and further removed from the immediate aftermath of the Cold War and of the shadow of postmodernism.Adorno’s insistence on the radical autonomy of the artwork has much to offer contemporary discussions of art and the aesthetic in search of new responses to the pervasive effects of a neoliberal art market and culture industry. Focusing specifically on Adorno’s engagement with literary works, Hohendahl shows how radically transformative Adorno’s ideas have been and how thoroughly they have shaped current discussions in aesthetics. Among the topics he considers are the role of art in modernism and postmodernism, the truth claims of artworks, the function of the ugly in modern artworks, the precarious value of the literary tradition, and the surprising significance of realism for Adorno.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAesthetics, Germany20th century. 0aAesthetics, German. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEurope. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146928240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469282423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801469282/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5